  "prompt": "What's difference between air compressor and screw compressor?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between air compressors and screw compressors:\n\nAir Compressor (General Term):\n- Broad category of machines that compress air\n- Multiple types (piston, rotary, centrifugal)\n- Varies in size and application\n- Can use different compression mechanisms\n\nScrew Compressor (Specific Type):\n- Uses two interlocking rotary screws to compress air\n- Continuous compression process\n- More efficient than piston compressors\n- Lower maintenance requirements\n- Typically used in industrial/commercial applications\n- Smoother air delivery\n- Higher capacity and continuous operation\n- Less mechanical friction\n- More consistent air pressure\n\nKey Distinctions:\n1. Mechanism: Rotary screw vs. various compression methods\n2. Efficiency: Screw compressors generally more efficient\n3. Noise level: Screw compressors typically quieter\n4. Complexity: Screw compressors more technologically advanced\n5. Cost: Screw compressors usually more expensive initially\n\nEssentially, a screw compressor is a specific type of air compressor with unique characteristics and advantages.",
